    "queryId": "query_1753114669914_2mrsqmq",
    "htmlContent": "<h2>Hanoi has just announced that it will ban diesel and petrol motorcycles from July 2026, with the hope of reducing air pollution in the city. People criticised this policy since lots of people&#039;s livelihoods depend on the two-wheelers, and infrastructure for a wide adoption of electric vehicles in Hanoi is limited. \n\nIs the time for implementing this policy too rushed? What and how long does it take for Hanoi to develop infrastructure and other supporting mechanisms for this transition?</h2>\n            <div class=\"attribution\">Generated by Cirdi on Monday, July 21, 2025</div>\n            <div class=\"generation-stats\"><span> Tokens: 0 in, 3,899 out. LLM cost: 0.78 cent. Self hosting cost: 1.03 cent (H100 VPS hourly rate for 12.35s.). </span></div>\n            <div class=\"settings-stats\">Retrieval en mode hyde limitÃ© Ã  20 segments. GÃ©nÃ©ration avec mistral/mistral-medium-latest limitÃ© Ã  1024 tokens out.</div>\n            <hr/>\n    <p>The timeline for implementing the policy to ban diesel and petrol motorcycles in Hanoi by July 2026 is indeed ambitious, and several factors need to be considered to determine if it is too rushed.</p>\n<h3>Infrastructure Development</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>Charging Infrastructure</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Developing a robust charging infrastructure is crucial for the widespread adoption of electric vehicles (EVs). For instance, France aimed to have 4.4 million charging points by 2020, but as of December 2015, there were only around 10,000 public charging points <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-hal-hal-01688931-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"6c51799b-1b9f-574a-baef-6b1df8a453f4\"\n                              >[1a]</a>. This indicates that developing such infrastructure can take significant time and investment.</li>\n<li>Vietnam has seen a market shift towards electric scooters without substantial government subsidies, suggesting that some infrastructure development can occur organically <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-hal-hal-01274178-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"33e250a4-a5f9-536d-b37f-9da53b4cd246\"\n                              >[2a]</a>. However, a more structured and rapid development would require targeted policies and investments.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong>Electric Grid and Smart Systems</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Integrating EVs into the smart grid and ensuring that the electric grid can handle the increased load is essential. This includes developing systems to manage the intermittency of renewable energy sources and ensuring grid stability <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-hal-hal-04155272-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"e3d6383b-a036-547d-822e-5f31ce001a56\"\n                              >[3a]</a>.</li>\n<li>Vietnam's Power Development Plan 8 (PDP8) highlights the need for significant investments in grid development and energy storage solutions to support renewable energy integration <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-hal-tel-00593573-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"f65310eb-58e8-5e4e-bd4e-d6c63d3d62a9\"\n                              >[4a]</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Supporting Mechanisms</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>Financial and Policy Support</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Financial mechanisms and policy support are critical. Vietnam's PDP8 aims to mobilize significant international financing, including a Just Energy Transition Partnership (JETP) that aims to raise $15.5 billion over the next 3 to 5 years <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-doi-10-3917-med-205-0115-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"71c51e6a-d2dc-51ed-b82c-414428035e1a\"\n                              >[5a]</a>. Such financial support can accelerate the development of necessary infrastructure.</li>\n<li>Policies such as feed-in tariffs, tax reductions, and incentives for EV adoption can also play a significant role. For example, France introduced incentives for electric vehicle purchasers to stimulate sales <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-hal-hal-01692652-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"92510e61-226e-5085-916c-356780688c08\"\n                              >[6a]</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong>Technological Advancements</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Advancements in battery technology and the development of standards for EV infrastructure are crucial. Research and development in battery storage and EV infrastructure need to be intensified to support the transition <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-hal-hal-04155272-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"e3d6383b-a036-547d-822e-5f31ce001a56\"\n                              >[3a]</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Timeline and Feasibility</h3>\n<p>Given the context, a timeline of approximately two years (from 2024 to 2026) to develop the necessary infrastructure and supporting mechanisms is highly ambitious. Here are some considerations:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>Infrastructure Development Time</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Developing charging infrastructure and upgrading the electric grid can take several years. For example, France's experience shows that even with significant efforts, developing millions of charging points can take a decade or more <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-hal-hal-01688931-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"6c51799b-1b9f-574a-baef-6b1df8a453f4\"\n                              >[1a]</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong>Financial and Policy Implementation</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Mobilizing financial resources and implementing supportive policies can also take time. The JETP aims to raise funds over the next 3 to 5 years, indicating that significant financial support may not be immediately available <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-doi-10-3917-med-205-0115-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"71c51e6a-d2dc-51ed-b82c-414428035e1a\"\n                              >[5a]</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong>Market and Technological Readiness</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>While there is a market shift towards electric scooters, ensuring that the technology and market are ready for a complete transition by 2026 is challenging. Continuous technological advancements and market readiness are essential <a class=\"citation-bracket\"\n                              href=\"#cite-hal-hal-01274178-msg-1753114718896\"\n                              data-chunk-id=\"33e250a4-a5f9-536d-b37f-9da53b4cd246\"\n                              >[2a]</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>In summary, while the policy to ban diesel and petrol motorcycles by July 2026 is a bold step towards reducing air pollution, the timeline is indeed rushed. Developing the necessary infrastructure, securing financial support, and ensuring technological and market readiness typically require more time. A more realistic timeline might involve a phased approach, with initial steps focusing on developing infrastructure and supportive policies, followed by a gradual transition to electric vehicles.</p>\n\n        <div class=\"bibliography-container\">\n            <div class=\"bibliography-header\">\n                Pour en savoir plus:\n            </div>\n            \n        <div class=\"document-item\" id=\"cite-hal-hal-01688931-msg-1753114718896\">\n            <div class=\"document-number\" style=\"margin-right: 0.5em;\">1a</div>\n            <div class=\"document-content\">\n                <h4 class=\"document-title\"\n                    data-doc-title=\"Pathways to deep decarbonization of the passenger transport sector in France\"\n                    data-doc-description=\"\"\n                    data-doc-authors=\"Yann Briand, Julien Lefevre, Jean-Michel Cayla (2017)\"\n                    data-doc-year=\"2017\"\n                    onmouseover=\"showTooltip(event, this)\"\n                    onmouseout=\"hideTooltip()\">\n                    Pathways to deep decarbonization of the passenger transport sector in France\n                </h4>\n                <p class=\"document-authors\">Yann Briand, Julien Lefevre, Jean-Michel Cayla (2017)</p>\n                <p class=\"document-links\">\n            <a href=\"https://hal.science/hal-01688931\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 flex items-center\">\n                <span class=\"mr-1\">ðŸ”—</span>\n                HALId: hal-01688931\n            </a>\n        </p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    \n        <div class=\"document-item\" id=\"cite-hal-hal-01274178-msg-1753114718896\">\n            <div class=\"document-number\" style=\"margin-right: 0.5em;\">2a</div>\n            <div class=\"document-content\">\n                <h4 class=\"document-title\"\n                    data-doc-title=\"Rest in peace Moped, electric scooters are there\"\n                    data-doc-description=\"In the last decade two-wheeler electric vehicles have been taking over the streets of Asian capitals, to the point that it is time to declare the gas moped commercially dead. Rest in peace\"\n                    data-doc-authors=\"Minh Ha-Duong (2016)\"\n                    data-doc-year=\"2016\"\n                    onmouseover=\"showTooltip(event, this)\"\n                    onmouseout=\"hideTooltip()\">\n                    Rest in peace Moped, electric scooters are there\n                </h4>\n                <p class=\"document-authors\">Minh Ha-Duong (2016)</p>\n                <p class=\"document-links\">\n            <a href=\"https://hal.science/hal-01274178\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 flex items-center\">\n                <span class=\"mr-1\">ðŸ”—</span>\n                HALId: hal-01274178\n            </a>\n        </p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    \n        <div class=\"document-item\" id=\"cite-hal-hal-04155272-msg-1753114718896\">\n            <div class=\"document-number\" style=\"margin-right: 0.5em;\">3a</div>\n            <div class=\"document-content\">\n                <h4 class=\"document-title\"\n                    data-doc-title=\"International collaboration on the energy transition in Vietnam\"\n                    data-doc-description=\"Many developing countries, including Vietnam, are striving to transform their energy systems into more sustainable ones. They are leveraging initiatives like the Just Energy Transition Partnership (JETP) with the G7. Although Vietnam&#39;s participation in the JETP is a vital step in its journey towards clean energy, it also faces certain implementation challenges. This address will delve into Vietnam&#39;s energy transition journey, considering five key perspectives: international cooperation, governance structures, considerations of justice and equity, technology solutions, and innovative financing methods. International partnerships are crucial to share knowledge, bear costs, and reap benefits. However, larger agreements sometimes face limitations, and more focused coalitions can assist in overcoming these. Vietnam&#39;s Power Development Plan 8 (PDP8) provides a roadmap for the future but will require adjustments and input from different stakeholders to ensure its effectiveness. A just transition demands consideration of several facets of justice, including solutions that are specific to Vietnam and take into account vulnerable communities and workers affected by the transition. Adopting a comprehensive approach that combines foundational research, new technologies, and deployable solutions can spur innovation. Likewise, legal frameworks encouraging private investment can accelerate the transition. In conclusion, while Vietnam&#39;s energy transition is progressing, there is still a long way to go. Recommendations include boosting stakeholder engagement, refining the mix of planning and market mechanisms, conducting assessments to ensure equity, investing in applicable technologies, and creating supportive legal and financial structures. Strengthened collaborations, both at multilateral and bilateral levels, can aid Vietnam in its journey towards a sustainable and prosperous energy future.\"\n                    data-doc-authors=\"Minh Ha-Duong (2023)\"\n                    data-doc-year=\"2023\"\n                    onmouseover=\"showTooltip(event, this)\"\n                    onmouseout=\"hideTooltip()\">\n                    International collaboration on the energy transition in Vietnam\n                </h4>\n                <p class=\"document-authors\">Minh Ha-Duong (2023)</p>\n                <p class=\"document-links\">\n            <a href=\"https://hal.science/hal-04155272\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 flex items-center\">\n                <span class=\"mr-1\">ðŸ”—</span>\n                HALId: hal-04155272\n            </a>\n        </p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    \n        <div class=\"document-item\" id=\"cite-hal-tel-00593573-msg-1753114718896\">\n            <div class=\"document-number\" style=\"margin-right: 0.5em;\">4a</div>\n            <div class=\"document-content\">\n                <h4 class=\"document-title\"\n                    data-doc-title=\"Programming Sustainable Development in a Developing Country: A Social Optimization of the Vietnamese Power Sector A\"\n                    data-doc-description=\"The kernel of this dissertation aims to exploit by optimisation methods and empirical studies the issues of sustainable development in the Vietnamese power sector for the next thirty years. It then examines the ways to implement sustainable energy options for the power sector in practice. To accomplish these two objectives, the study focuses on different, but related, issues with these two methodologies: (i) In the first part, we develop the bottom-up Integrated Resource Planning (IRP) model to provide a more exhaustive assessment of the current state and future prospects for the Vietnamese power sector in next three decades. Then, using a comparative analysis and a vulnerability analysis that is based on the IRP simulation, we analyze energy-development-related vulnerabilities that the sector could face, in terms of economic and socioenvironmental dimensions. We further develop the IRP model, in such a way representing realistically the marginal abatement costs of carbon emission reduction by considering non-zero carbon values and carbon emission constraints, in order to simulate sustainable energy supply options for the power sector. (ii) In the second part, we study the major barriers against the wider adoption of sustainable energy development options in practice by using analytical hierarchy process-based formal surveys among national experts. Then, we use an empirical analysis approach to examine different appropriate policy means including incentive instruments/schemes and sector reform for such sustainability of the power sector. To the end, we analyze the access to feasible financing sources for sustainable development in the Vietnamese power sector.\"\n                    data-doc-authors=\"Nhan Thanh Nguyen (2011)\"\n                    data-doc-year=\"2011\"\n                    onmouseover=\"showTooltip(event, this)\"\n                    onmouseout=\"hideTooltip()\">\n                    Programming Sustainable Development in a Developing Country: A Social Optimization of the Vietnamese Power Sector A\n                </h4>\n                <p class=\"document-authors\">Nhan Thanh Nguyen (2011)</p>\n                <p class=\"document-links\">\n            <a href=\"https://hal.science/tel-00593573\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 flex items-center\">\n                <span class=\"mr-1\">ðŸ”—</span>\n                HALId: tel-00593573\n            </a>\n        </p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    \n        <div class=\"document-item\" id=\"cite-doi-10-3917-med-205-0115-msg-1753114718896\">\n            <div class=\"document-number\" style=\"margin-right: 0.5em;\">5a</div>\n            <div class=\"document-content\">\n                <h4 class=\"document-title\"\n                    data-doc-title=\"Vietnam at the dawn of its energy transition\"\n                    data-doc-description=\"Vietnam&#39;s Power Development Plan 8 (PDP8) sets a course for the country&#39;s energy transition to carbon neutrality by 2050. The plan targets significant growth in renewable energy, diversification of energy sources, and reduced reliance on imported coal. However, implementing PDP8 poses considerable challenges, including securing an estimated $13 billion annually for new power capacities and grid upgrades, expanding the power grid to accommodate more renewables, and managing the risk of dependence on imported liquefied natural gas (LNG). The success of this plan could provide a model for other middle-income countries undergoing similar energy transitions.\"\n                    data-doc-authors=\"Minh Ha-Duong (2024)\"\n                    data-doc-year=\"2024\"\n                    onmouseover=\"showTooltip(event, this)\"\n                    onmouseout=\"hideTooltip()\">\n                    Vietnam at the dawn of its energy transition\n                </h4>\n                <p class=\"document-authors\">Minh Ha-Duong (2024)</p>\n                <p class=\"document-links\">\n            <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.3917/med.205.0115\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 flex items-center\">\n                <span class=\"mr-1\">ðŸ”—</span>\n                DOI: 10.3917/med.205.0115\n            </a>\n        \n            <a href=\"https://hal.science/hal-04571483\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 flex items-center\">\n                <span class=\"mr-1\">ðŸ”—</span>\n                HALId: hal-04571483\n            </a>\n        </p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    \n        <div class=\"document-item\" id=\"cite-hal-hal-01692652-msg-1753114718896\">\n            <div class=\"document-number\" style=\"margin-right: 0.5em;\">6a</div>\n            <div class=\"document-content\">\n                <h4 class=\"document-title\"\n                    data-doc-title=\"Pathways to Deep Decarbonization in France\"\n                    data-doc-description=\"Le rapport DDPP France Ã©value deux trajectoires contrastÃ©es de dÃ©carbonisation Ã  lâ€™horizon 2050 pour la France, lâ€™une misant sur une baisse ambitieuse de la demande dâ€™Ã©nergie, lâ€™autre sur une forte dÃ©carbonisation de lâ€™Ã©nergie. La premiÃ¨re trajectoire sâ€™articule autour dâ€™une rÃ©duction de 50% de la consommation dâ€™Ã©nergie finale en 2050, objectif phare de la rÃ©cente loi sur la Transition EnergÃ©tique pour la Croissance Verte. Or les obstacles Ã  la rÃ©alisation dâ€™un tel objectif sont nombreux, notamment pour la mise en Å“uvre effective dâ€™un vaste programme dâ€™efficacitÃ© Ã©nergÃ©tique et pour rÃ©aliser les inflexions nÃ©cessaires dans les transports. Si les politiques climatiques Ã©chouaient Ã  rÃ©aliser un tel objectif de rÃ©duction de la demande dâ€™Ã©nergie, il faudrait par contre mobiliser des potentiels supplÃ©mentaires dâ€™Ã©nergie dÃ©carbonÃ©e. Ceci nâ€™est pas sans poser dâ€™autres problÃ¨mes, tels que le dÃ©ploiement de centrales nuclÃ©aires de 3e gÃ©nÃ©ration, de la technologie de capture et sÃ©questration du carbone ou le dÃ©veloppement Ã  grande Ã©chelle de la biomasse Ã©nergie. Le rapport analyse les politiques sectorielles Ã  mettre en Å“uvre et leurs obstacles, et mÃ¨ne une Ã©valuation Ã©conomique de ces deux trajectoires. La prise en compte des incertitudes propres Ã  chacune de ces trajectoires montre quâ€™une stratÃ©gie axÃ©e sur une forte rÃ©duction de la demande est plus robuste quâ€™une stratÃ©gie privilÃ©giant la dÃ©carbonisation de lâ€™offre Ã©nergÃ©tique : en rÃ©duisant le besoin en Ã©nergie dÃ©carbonÃ©e, elle laisse plus de marge de manÅ“uvre en cas dâ€™Ã©chec des politiques de rÃ©duction de demande. Enfin, mÃªme si la dÃ©carbonisation de lâ€™Ã©conomie gÃ©nÃ¨re de la croissance et de lâ€™emploi sur le moyen terme, des coÃ»ts dâ€™ajustement sur le court terme apparaissent, ce qui est en mesure dâ€™entraver toute dÃ©cision politique dans ce domaine. Des propositions sont faites pour permettre de rÃ©duire ces coÃ»ts dâ€™ajustement et favoriser ainsi le dÃ©clenchement rapide de la transition Ã©nergÃ©tique.\"\n                    data-doc-authors=\"Sandrine Mathy, Patrick Criqui, Jean Charles Hourcade (2015)\"\n                    data-doc-year=\"2015\"\n                    onmouseover=\"showTooltip(event, this)\"\n                    onmouseout=\"hideTooltip()\">\n                    Pathways to Deep Decarbonization in France\n                </h4>\n                <p class=\"document-authors\">Sandrine Mathy, Patrick Criqui, Jean Charles Hourcade (2015)</p>\n                <p class=\"document-links\">\n            <a href=\"https://hal.science/hal-01692652\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 flex items-center\">\n                <span class=\"mr-1\">ðŸ”—</span>\n                HALId: hal-01692652\n            </a>\n        </p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    \n        </div>\n    "
